<Content>Do hotel designers ever stay in their hotels? On the plus side - The location of Le Germain is very convenient for tourists and visitors to the Convention Center.Beds are very, very comfortable.Breakfast is good, although not outstanding.Service was generally friendly, pleasant and helpful, except for doormen who were always too busy chatting to their colleagues to open doors.The negatives were -The hotel is very highly designed. The most prominent feature is an open window between the shower and the bedroom. This may be wonderful for honeymooners, but I suspect that most guests prefer a little privacy when they shower. Also, who really wants to enjoy a view of a messy bathroom from their bedroom. Fortunately, one can use blinds to close the open window. As in many hotel rooms, lighting is extremely inadequate. All the fixtures are attractive, but they only light the perimeter of the room. We kept misplacing our fashionably black clothing in the middle of the room.In this 21st century hotel, there was only one useable electric plug in the room. When we asked what we were supposed to do with our computer, cellphones, blackberries, etc., maintenance brought us an extension cord. Odd we thought.The room had a thermostat, but it had no influence on the room temperature. Considering the many imperfections, the price, after all the now usual nickel and dimeing, was very high. 
