<Author>SandyB
<Content>It's the little things at Le Germain Hotel ... We thoroughly enjoyed our long weekend stay at Le Germain Hotel in Toronto (although the changing exchange rate between the American and Canadian dollar made it more expensive than we'd anticipated). First of all, it has a fabulous location in the middle of the Entertainment district. We enjoy walking and, from Le Germain, we were able to foot it to Queen Street, Kensington Martket, Chinatown, and even Little Italy. (We enjoy a more neighborhoody, authentic experience, so stayed away from the Bloor Street high couture thing.) We had a standard Queen room, but found it absolutely wonderful. Nothing standard about it -- the best bed I think I've ever slept in, outfitted with high count cotton sheets, down comforter, 4 huge down pillows ... ahhh. There was a large comfortable chair with a large, soft throw, for curling up and reading. One side of the shower is a glass wall (visible from the room, with blinds for the more discrete). The shower itself is wonderful with a choice of either a ceiling rainshower or hand-held shower head that can be attached to a lower level (for shorter people, or those who don't want to wash their hair). There were shelves and cubby holes everywhere in the large room that enabled you to spread out and really claim the space. Also, there were many large drawers and two closets for hanging articles, which also had shelves. There were many small touches throughout the room that showed alot of thought had gone into the design -- for example, a 3-way mirror mounted on the wall at face level that opened like a cabinet and, below that, a drop down shelf to hold make-up or whatever. Also, the lighting was varied and generous. I (as opposed to another post) enjoyed the breakfast food: coffee, expresso, juice, homemade jams, hard-boiled eggs, breads, pastries, bagels, croissants, fruits(citrus' membranes removed), crepes, muesli ... dunno what else you could want, unless you were looking for fried food. There were two servers who were helping all the while and remembered the next day that I liked cappucino with extra milk and brought it over immediately. A nice and welcomed touch. The lobby has two levels with a glassed-in fireplace separating the two burning real wood, as well as a laptop connected to the internet, comfortable furniture, a floor-to-ceiling library, and a free expresso machine. I would term the decor as european sleek, but very comfortable. The hotel staff is young, extremely polite, and eager to please. They've obviously been well-trained. There was also a free, fitness room on the top floor with a weight machine, two treadmills, and an eliptical trainer. All the cardio machines had individual TVs. I found the one drawback being the concierge desk. They tried to be helpful, but really weren't well versed in the city. I was wondering about a few places I had read about in various travel books, and they weren't familiar with them. They were very responsive with specific requests like restaurant reservations. I asked my questions elsewhere. 
